&gt; Hi Ken,
&gt; 
&gt;&gt; Could you tell me a little more about your NEAT Python project? I
&gt;&gt; have heard a bit about it but I don&#39;t know what it&#39;s being used for or
&gt;&gt; whether it is intended to be a general-purpose tool for the public?
&gt; 
&gt; We started our own Python implementation because we felt that&#39;s easier
&gt; to extend and develop. I&#39;ve also taken a look at PyNEAT (another older
&gt; NEAT Python version) but I couldn&#39;t make it work. It seems that it&#39;s
&gt; not being developed any longer.
&gt; 
&gt; Our version is closely based on your C++ sources and the great
&gt; Simmerson&#39;s Java version. But our approach was a modular one. Well,
&gt; any OOP based version is modular enough, but we&#39;ve tried to separate
&gt; the concept of the experiment from the main code, meaning that you
&gt; basically need to import the libraries, specify the config parameters
&gt; and write a fitness function.
&gt; 
&gt; Although everything seems to be working (including the XOR example),
&gt; it&#39;s not &quot;officially&quot; released since I need to finish the FAQ and add
&gt; a basic tutorial. But it&#39;s rather simple to checkout from the SVN
&gt; repository and play with the XOR example. The only requirement is
&gt; Python 2.5 (you still need some other libraries in order to plot the
&gt; results).
&gt; 
&gt; The NEAT-Python project URL is: http://code.google.com/p/neat-python
&gt; (licensed under GPLv3)
&gt; 
&gt; The name &quot;NEAT-Python&quot; is not a a very good one, I&#39;d really like to
&gt; have something similar to PyNEAT, but that&#39;s already taken.
&gt; Suggestions are welcome!
&gt; 
&gt; By the way, Peter B. has been working with NEAT-Python for a while now
&gt; (he&#39;s on this group).
&gt; 
&gt;&gt; If so, would you like me to link it from the NEAT Users page and my
&gt;&gt; homepage?
&gt; 
&gt; Sure, that will help the project to reach a wider audience :-)
&gt; 
&gt; Thanks,
&gt; Cesar
